<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCCA83CFEE8F63EE7A3F9B8" bold="true" box="[381,392,1577,1596]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">‒</emphasis>
caudal view, 6 
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCCA83CFD98F63EE433F9B8" bold="true" box="[525,536,1577,1596]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="41">‒</emphasis>
lateral view).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="BD8D60B1FFCDA83DFFE4F614E4B3F9B5" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468285" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4468285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468285/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" startId="3.[113,150,1539,1558]" targetBox="[121,1085,221,1510]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCDA83DFFE4F614E4B3F9B5" blockId="3.[113,1090,1539,1585]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
Figs 7–10. Dorsal view of 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCDA83DFECFF614E791F991" authorityName="Berthold" authorityYear="1827" box="[346,442,1539,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCDA83DFECFF614E791F991" box="[346,442,1539,1557]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Nematopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. 7 – 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCDA83DFD99F614E4C4F992" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[524,751,1539,1558]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCDA83DFD99F614E47FF992" box="[524,596,1539,1558]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">N. indus</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
. 8 – 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCDA83DFC8EF614E229F992" authority="Laporte, 1832" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1832" box="[795,1026,1539,1558]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nervosus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCDA83DFC8EF614E5ABF991" box="[795,896,1539,1557]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">N. nervosus</emphasis>
Laporte, 1832
</taxonomicName>
. 9 – 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCDA83DFBB8F614E6EDF9B4" authority="Brailovsky, 2015" authorityName="Brailovsky" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persuasus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCDA83DFBB8F614E6EDF9B4" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">N. persuasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="C0B55150FFCDA83DFF59F609E724F9B5" box="[204,271,1566,1585]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
10 – 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCDA83DFEABF609E4BFF9B5" authority="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003" authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2003" box="[318,660,1565,1585]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCDA83DFEABF609E7B5F9B4" box="[318,414,1565,1584]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">N. spinulus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="8D634DC8FFCDA83DFE36F609E4BFF9B5" author="BRAILOVSKY H. &amp; BARRERA E." box="[419,660,1566,1585]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" pagination="159 - 175" refId="ref3566" refString="BRAILOVSKY H. &amp; BARRERA E. 2003: Eight new species of Nematopus Berthold (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Coreidae: Nematopodini) from Central and South America. Pan-Pacific Entomologist 79: 159 - 175." type="journal article" year="2003">Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F0CCE74CFE36" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
Pronotum wider than long; calli barely raised above pronotal disk; calli, anterior margin and basal third of anterolateral margins broken up into a number of small tubercles; humeral angles expanded into medium-sized spine directed outward, clearly upward, and apically subacute; triangular process of posterolateral angle elongate, reaching anterior margin of scutellum, and apically almost rounded; mesosternum lacking sulcation; metasternal scent gland ostiole placed relatively close to lateral margin of metapleuron (
<figureCitation id="71C92CBCFFCAA83AFC0AF16CE5CFFE16" box="[927,996,379,402]" captionStart="Figs 1‒6" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[169,1110,227,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-76@2.[163,1115,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1‒6. Nematopus spp. 1‒2 ‒ pronotum: 1 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003; 2 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. 3‒6 ‒ male genital capsule: 3‒4 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. (3 ‒ caudal view, 4 ‒ lateral view). 5‒6 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003 (5 ‒ caudal view, 6 ‒ lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Scutellum transversely striate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F1ACE78DFDF6" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Legs. Trochanters unarmed; fore and middle femora armed with two stout subapical spines; hind femur incrassate in both sexes, but much more so in male, dorsally smooth and ventrally with double row of small irregular tubercles, two pairs of stout subapical spines and one slender medium-sized spine near middle third; hind tibiae sulcate, inner face with irregular tiny granules and one small cone-shaped spine near middle third; hind tibiae not armed distally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F26CE24CFC96" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
Abdomen. Posterior angle of connexival segments IV to VII with short spine conspicuously acute; abdominal spiracles situated nearer anterior than lateral margin. Posteroventral margin of genital capsule with mesial keel, apically split in two long branches resembling winged expansions pointing to the sides and leaving concavity between them; keel delimited laterally by two short, strong projections which distally become sharper and slightly spiniform (
<figureCitation id="71C92CBCFFCAA83AFC6EF2ECE270FC96" box="[1019,1115,763,786]" captionStart="Figs 1‒6" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[169,1110,227,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-76@2.[163,1115,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1‒6. Nematopus spp. 1‒2 ‒ pronotum: 1 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003; 2 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. 3‒6 ‒ male genital capsule: 3‒4 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. (3 ‒ caudal view, 4 ‒ lateral view). 5‒6 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003 (5 ‒ caudal view, 6 ‒ lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Figs 3–4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F30CE4A8FC16" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFF20F30CE77BFCB6" box="[181,336,795,818]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Measurements</emphasis>
(mm). Total body length 16.40. Head length 1.48; width across eyes 2.20; interocular width 1.20; interocellar width 0.40; preocular length 1.00; length of antennal segments: I – 3.24; II – 2.68; III – 2.40; IV – 5.60. Pronotal length 2.92; width across humeral angles 4.92. Scutellar length 2.32; width 1.84.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F38DE7E5FBF6" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFF20F38DE724FC36" bold="true" box="[181,271,922,946]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Female.</emphasis>
Habitus and color similar to male 
<typeStatus id="36498E9BFFCAA83AFD1EF38CE4C7FC36" box="[651,748,923,946]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">holotype</typeStatus>
. Pronotum with collar and anterior margin olive-brown; connexival segments VIII and IX black with anterior margin castaneous orange; hind femur yellow with pale green sheen and posterior third brown; dorsal abdominal segments VIII and IX dark yellowish orange; outer margin of metapleura and pleural margins of abdominal sterna III to VII tinged with green; gonocoxae I dark brown; paratergite VIII yellow with upper and inner border dark brown; paratergite IX dark brown with upper border yellow. Hind tibiae unarmed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF20F46CE4A8FB76" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFF20F46CE77BFB16" box="[181,336,1147,1170]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Measurements</emphasis>
(mm). Total body length 18.55. Head length 1.52; width across eyes 2.40; interocular width 1.30; interocellar width 0.46; preocular length 1.02; length of antennal segments: I – 3.00; II – 2.64; III – 2.48; IV – 5.64. Pronotal length 3.60; width across humeral angles 5.40. Scutellar length 2.72; width 2.36.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1E863B2FFCAA83AFF02F4ECE4A1F9B6" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCAA83AFF02F4ECE4A1F9B6" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,1586]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFF02F4ECE7BFFA96" bold="true" box="[151,404,1275,1298]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is related to 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCAA83AFD7AF4ECE6E7FAB6" authority="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003" authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2003" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFD7AF4ECE541FA96" box="[751,874,1274,1298]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">N. spinulus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="8D634DC8FFCAA83AFCE6F4ECE6E7FAB6" author="BRAILOVSKY H. &amp; BARRERA E." pageId="4" pageNumber="43" pagination="159 - 175" refId="ref3566" refString="BRAILOVSKY H. &amp; BARRERA E. 2003: Eight new species of Nematopus Berthold (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Coreidae: Nematopodini) from Central and South America. Pan-Pacific Entomologist 79: 159 - 175." type="journal article" year="2003">
Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 
<quantity id="2E0A9DDCFFCAA83AFF02F50CE6E7FAB6" box="[151,204,1307,1330]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.087619999999999" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" unit="in" value="2003.0">2003</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in having the humeral angles strongly expanded (
<figureCitation id="71C92CBCFFCAA83AFD41F50CE569FAB6" box="[724,834,1307,1330]" captionStart="Figs 7–10" captionStartId="3.[113,150,1539,1558]" captionTargetBox="[121,1085,221,1510]" captionTargetId="figure-42@3.[121,1086,221,1510]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 7–10. Dorsal view of Nematopus spp. 7 – N. indus (Linnaeus, 1758). 8 – N. nervosus Laporte, 1832. 9 – N. persuasus sp. nov. 10 – N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468285/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCAA83AFCFBF50CE5CFFAB6" authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2003" box="[878,996,1306,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFCFBF50CE5CFFAB6" box="[878,996,1306,1330]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">N. spinulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the humeral angles are directed outward and apically rounded, the triangular processes of posterolateral angles of pronotum are small, broad, and apically subacute, and the color of pronotal disk pale orange with punctures chestnut orange, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCAA83AFD61F56CE554FA16" authority="Brailovsky, 2015" authorityName="Brailovsky" authorityYear="2015" box="[756,895,1403,1426]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persuasus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCAA83AFD61F56CE554FA16" box="[756,895,1403,1426]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">N. persuasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="C0B55150FFCAA83AFC13F56CE5F7FA16" box="[902,988,1403,1426]" pageId="4" pageNumber="43" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the humeral angles are strongly expanded with a medium-sized spine directed outward, clearly upward and apically subacute, the triangular processes are elongate, apically almost rounded, and the pronotal disk is yellow, punctures castaneous and anterolateral and posterolateral margins, and humeral angles yellow with olive-green to pale green sheen (
<figureCitation id="71C92CBCFFCAA83AFCD1F5ECE58FF996" box="[836,932,1531,1554]" captionStart="Figs 1‒6" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[169,1110,227,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-76@2.[163,1115,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1‒6. Nematopus spp. 1‒2 ‒ pronotum: 1 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003; 2 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. 3‒6 ‒ male genital capsule: 3‒4 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. (3 ‒ caudal view, 4 ‒ lateral view). 5‒6 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003 (5 ‒ caudal view, 6 ‒ lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
). The male genital capsule differs in the general shape (
<figureCitation id="71C92CBCFFCAA83AFD89F60CE455F9B6" box="[540,638,1563,1586]" captionStart="Figs 1‒6" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[169,1110,227,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-76@2.[163,1115,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1‒6. Nematopus spp. 1‒2 ‒ pronotum: 1 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003; 2 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. 3‒6 ‒ male genital capsule: 3‒4 ‒ N. persuasus sp. nov. (3 ‒ caudal view, 4 ‒ lateral view). 5‒6 ‒ N. spinulus Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2003 (5 ‒ caudal view, 6 ‒ lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="43">Figs 3–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1E863B2FFCBA83BFFE4F0CBE741FE97" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCBA83BFFE4F0CBE741FE97" blockId="5.[113,1089,220,307]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCBA83BFFE4F0CBE6D9FF77" bold="true" box="[113,242,220,243]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName id="2EF24BBAFFCBA83BFD08F0CBE523FF77" authorityName="Brailovsky" authorityYear="2015" box="[669,776,220,243]" class="Insecta" family="Coreidae" genus="Nematopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persuasus">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCBA83BFD08F0CBE523FF77" box="[669,776,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">persuasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCBA83BFC82F0CBE50FFF77" box="[791,804,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">a</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCBA83BFCA4F0CBE579FF77" box="[817,850,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">um</emphasis>
), meaning persuasive, convincing, believable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1E863B2FFCBA83BFFE4F10BE45EFEB7" box="[113,629,284,307]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E94D3039FFCBA83BFFE4F10BE45EFEB7" blockId="5.[113,1089,220,307]" box="[113,629,284,307]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="DB86EC2BFFCBA83BFFE4F10BE72FFEB7" bold="true" box="[113,260,284,307]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from 
<collectingCountry id="91E570A9FFCBA83BFE45F10BE45BFEB7" box="[464,624,284,307]" name="French Guiana" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
